The Measuring House was the Great Oasis tri-function core: observatory, archive, and court operating as a single integrated institution.
It combined celestial observation for calendar calibration, physical measurement standards for trade certification, and legal adjudication of weight and volume disputes.
The institution was the operational heart of the Keepers of Measure's Great Oasis governance and the physical home of the Measure Script's master reference tablets.
Three functions occupied three wings of a single building: the Elevation Tower (observatory), the Tablet Hall (archive), and the Witness Chamber (courthouse).
All three functions were administratively unified under a single officer, the Master Measurer, because the Keepers believed accurate law required accurate measurement and accurate time simultaneously.
The Measuring House issued route certifications, certified caravans' water-debt assessments, arbitrated trade disputes using reference weights, and maintained the solar calendar used across the oasis-pyramid corridor.
Its collapse during the Fracture Era left a governance vacuum that no single successor institution has filled — Midgaard holds some registry functions, Mafdet holds some measurement standards, and no one holds the calendar authority.
The Great Oasis Measuring House site is still identifiable; the Elevation Tower's foundations survive, and the Tablet Hall's floor plan has been archaeologically mapped.
The master reference tablets are partially recovered: several survived in Mafdet's Tide Ledger Hall (the Saltweight standard derives from them), and fragments appear in Midgaard's Violet Compact archive.
The Witness Chamber's records are the most complete loss: those documents recorded legal precedents for measurement disputes that are now unresolvable without reference.
Deltari water-readers maintain oral records of the Measuring House's aquifer assessment protocols that predate the written Measure Script.

