Midgaard traces part of its registry authority to the Measuring House's Witness Chamber. The Violet Compact's charter claims derivation from Keeper-era measurement law as a foundation for its occult oversight and standards-registry functions. The Measuring House's reference tablets, in fragmentary form, are among the Violet Compact archive's most protected holdings. Midgaard's position: registry authority passed to successors through institutional lineage, not physical continuity; Midgaard is the inland successor, Mafdet the maritime successor. The Charter Review Board has reviewed three cases citing Measuring House precedent; all three were accepted as historically valid but not currently binding. The Continuity faction wants to formally ratify the Measuring House lineage claim, strengthening Midgaard's authority over continental measurement standards. The Reckoning faction notes that the Measuring House held calendar authority, which no city currently claims, and asks why it was not inherited.

