Kowloon's Neon Covenant maintains calibrated weight standards tracing their lineage indirectly to the Measuring House through Deltari hydraulic records. The Deltari communities who pre-inhabited Kowloon's territory retained oral records of the Measuring House's aquifer and water-volume assessment protocols, which were incorporated into the Neon Covenant's standards system. Kowloon does not claim institutional succession from the Measuring House; it claims functional continuity through communities whose standards predated and outlasted it — a significant distinction. Both Midgaard and Kowloon invoke different ancestors for the same measurement authority. The standards are close enough for practical trade but not identical. Kowloon's position: a standard theoretically correct but practically disputed reduces throughput. The Measuring House's integrated three-function model is noted in Kowloon's history as the most efficient approach to civic standards governance ever documented.

