Kiess's anti-secrecy doctrine positions the Measuring House as the historical exemplar of transparent institutional governance: public observatory, accessible archive, witnessed court — all three functions open to public observation in principle. The Kiess three-power charter explicitly references this model. Kiess's route law includes measurement certification requirements tracing their form to Keeper-era Measuring House protocols, transmitted through caravan-league custom during the Fracture Era. Kiess's frontier measurement stations are designed on a simplified version of this model: each station maintains a reference weight set, a route log, and an arbitration function. The network as a whole is intended to function as the distributed analog of the Measuring House's unified system. Kiess considers the Measuring House's collapse a preventable catastrophe that resulted from centralization of irreplaceable functions; Kiess builds distributed networks that are less efficient but more survivable.

