Rakuen's Garden Ledger includes the Measuring House in its section on institutions whose collapse created governance voids persisting across multiple crisis periods. The calendar authority gap is a continuing practical problem: without a universally accepted calendar reference, inter-city coordination of seasonal trade events, planting cycles, and flood preparation depends on bilateral agreement rather than shared standard. Bilateral agreements are more fragile; Rakuen has experienced three inter-city scheduling failures in the current era that a common calendar would have prevented. Rakuen's proposal: establish a new tri-function institution at a neutral site with observatory, archive, and arbitration functions. Submitted twice; Midgaard declined to fund it, Kowloon declined to staff it, Kiess supported it but could not compel the others. Rakuen's position: the Measuring House's collapse is not ancient history — it is a continuing infrastructure gap producing ongoing coordination failures.

