Mafdet's Tide Ledger Hall holds the most complete surviving set of Measuring House reference weights in active use anywhere in the corridor. The Saltweight standard is calibrated against these, preserved by Ledger-Tariff era Shoreward Assessors when the Measuring House collapsed. Mafdet has not claimed institutional succession; the Claw Mark Registry's legal team considered the claim and rejected it: succession implies obligations as well as authority. Mafdet declines to absorb calendar governance and inland trade arbitration obligations alongside the measurement authority. The Shrine of the First Claw notes that the Measuring House's Witness Chamber combined measurement arbitration with oath-sealed testimony — essentially what the Shrine's Swift Court does for maritime disputes. This parallel is acknowledged as convergent development rather than direct lineage. The Measuring House's measurement function survived in Mafdet's standards system; its other functions did not survive elsewhere.

