Deltari oral records of the Measuring House's water-volume assessment protocols predate the Keeper-era written documentation of those same protocols. The Keepers formalized what the Deltari had already developed: methods for measuring water volume in cisterns, channels, and aquifer outputs with legal precision. Deltari in Midgaard's measurement offices cite this priority when questions of measurement authority arise: the Keepers recorded the standard; the Deltari invented it. Deltari measurement methodology uses Reed Law framework: water-volume is measured in flow-rate terms rather than static-volume terms, producing different legal results in water-debt disputes. For most trade purposes the two methods agree closely enough; for seasonal variation disputes, they can produce significantly different verdicts. The Measuring House's Witness Chamber arbitrated these disputes using both methodologies simultaneously. Its loss means no unified arbitration framework currently exists.

