Ushabti in Mafdet's legal community treat the Measuring House's Witness Chamber records as the most significant unrecovered body of judicial precedent in the corridor. The Chamber arbitrated measurement disputes using calibrated physical evidence and sworn witness simultaneously — exactly the judicial methodology Ushabti consider correct. Current measurement disputes without Chamber precedent must be resolved from first principles or partial reconstructions from fragmentary Keeper-era case notes. Ushabti find partial reconstruction legally adequate but institutionally insufficient: a reconstructed precedent has less authority than a surviving one, even if the reasoning is identical. Mafdet's Swift Court employs two Ushabti assessors for trade measurement disputes; their assessments carry judicial review weight rather than administrative weight. The running reconstruction is at thirty-seven resolved case types; the Ushabti estimate the Chamber handled at least two hundred distinct case types.
